Twitter Analysis

Progress Journals - Extended Tutorials

May 7, 2019

In this short tutorial we are going to learn how to obtain and analyze tweets using rtweet and tidytext packages. Our data of interest will be Good Omens tweets. Lets start with some prerequisites.

Preparations

  1. Go to Twitter Developers and create an app.
  2. Record Consumer API Key & Secret, and Access Token Key & Secret. A total of 4 garbled text.

Initialization

Load (and if not installed, install) the following packages.

options(stringsAsFactors=FALSE)
library(plyr)
library(tidyverse)
library(lubridate)
library(rtweet)
library(tidytext)
library(wordcloud)

##   secret: <hidden>
## <credentials> oauth_token, oauth_token_secret
## ---

Using create_token function, set your Twitter credentials. Replace the placeholders with your actual info.

  create_token(
    app = "APP_NAME",
    consumer_key = "CONSUMER_KEY",
    consumer_secret = "CONSUMER_SECRET",
    access_token = "ACCESS_TOKEN",
    access_secret = "ACCESS_SECRET"
  )

Now, you are ready to analyze data!

Getting Data from Twitter

Lets get 5000 tweets in English with #GoodOmens hashtag. Exclude retweets by setting include_rts parameter to FALSE.

tweets_raw <- search_tweets("#GoodOmens", n = 5000, include_rts = FALSE, lang = "en",retryonratelimit = TRUE)

Lets check the gathered information. In this query we have a data frame of 811 rows and 88 columns.

Text Mining

With several simple commands we will clean up Twitter chatter while maintaining Twitter properties such as mentions and hashtags. Using unnest_tokens we separated tweets into single words. By filtering stop words, we removed all irrelevant words that are essential to build a grammatically correct sentence. Then we do a word count to get the most popular words.

tweet_words <-
tweets_raw %>% 
  select(text) %>%
  unnest_tokens(word,text,token = "tweets") %>% 
  filter(!word %in% stop_words$word,
         !word %in% str_remove_all(stop_words$word, "'"),
         str_detect(word, "[a-z]")) 

tweet_words %>% count(word,sort=TRUE) %>% slice(1:20) %>% knitr::kable()

Sentiment Analysis

Sentiment analysis with tidytext is easy because of predefined libraries. Though you should be aware that not every sentiment library is useful to your data set. Here we are going to use Bing" sentiments with only negative and positive outcomes.

sentiments %>% filter(lexicon=="bing") %>% slice(1:10) %>% knitr::kable()
word sentiment lexicon score
2-faced negative bing NA
2-faces negative bing NA
a+ positive bing NA
abnormal negative bing NA
abolish negative bing NA
abominable negative bing NA
abominably negative bing NA
abominate negative bing NA
abomination negative bing NA
abort negative bing NA 
sentiment_words <-
tweet_words %>% 
  left_join(.,
    sentiments %>% filter(lexicon=="bing") %>% select(word,sentiment), 
    by="word"
  ) %>% 
  filter(!is.na(sentiment)) 

sentiment_words %>% slice(1:10) %>% knitr::kable()

Now lets finish this short analysis with another wordcloud. This time we are going to separate sentiments into two groups.

sentiment_frequency <-
sentiment_words %>% 
  count(word,sentiment) %>% 
  spread(sentiment,n,fill=0)

sentiment_matrix <-
sentiment_frequency %>%
  select(-word) %>% 
  as.matrix(.)

rownames(sentiment_matrix) <- sentiment_frequency$word

comparison.cloud(sentiment_matrix,colors = c("#F8766D", "#00BFC4"),
                 max.words = 100)
